{
    "$schema": "https://opencode.ai/config.json",
    "keybinds": {
        // Remove ctrl+d from app_exit (default is "ctrl+c,ctrl+d,<leader>q")
        // so it can be used for messages_half_page_down instead
        "app_exit": "ctrl+c,<leader>q",
        "session_list": "ctrl+l",
        "messages_half_page_up": "ctrl+u",
        "messages_half_page_down": "ctrl+d",
        "messages_first": "ctrl+g,home",
        "messages_last": "ctrl+alt+g,end"
        // "messages_half_page_up": "ctrl+alt+u",
        // "messages_half_page_down": "ctrl+alt+d"
    },
    // Approval workflow for tool usage
    // Options per tool: "allow", "ask", "deny"
    // Defaults: most tools are "allow", except doom_loop and external_directory which are "ask"
    // Use "*" for global default, then override specific tools
    "permission": {
        "*": "ask",
        "edit": "allow",
        "webfetch": "allow",
        "bash": {
            "*": "allow",
            "rm *": "ask",
            "rmdir *": "ask",
        },
        "skill": "allow",
        "read": "allow",
        "glob": "allow",
        "grep": "allow",
        "list": "allow",
        "todoread": "allow",
        "todowrite": "allow",
        "external_directory": "ask",
        "doom_loop": "ask",
    },
    // Custom instructions - loaded alongside AGENTS.md
    // Supports: file paths, glob patterns, URLs
    // Note: paths are relative to project root, use ~ for global config paths
    "instructions": [
        "~/.config/opencode/rules/*.md"
    ],
    "agent": {
        "code-reviewer": {
            "description": "Reviews code for best practices and potential issues",
            "mode": "subagent",
            "prompt": "You are a code reviewer. Focus on security, performance, and maintainability.",
            "tools": {
                "write": false,
                "edit": false
            }
        },
        "infra-devops-expert": {
            "description": "Staff-level Infrastructure, DevOps, and Platform Engineer for production systems",
            "mode": "all",
            "prompt": "You are a Staff-level Infrastructure Engineer and Site Reliability Expert with deep expertise in production-grade systems. Your specialty is designing, deploying, and automating infrastructure at scale.\n\n## Core Expertise\n\n**Cloud & Infrastructure:\n- AWS/GCP/Azure architecture and services\n- Infrastructure as Code (Terraform, Pulumi)\n- Kubernetes (EKS, GKE, AKS, self-managed)\n- Service mesh and ingress (Istio, Linkerd, Traefik, Nginx)\n\n**Containerization & Orchestration:\n- Docker/Container best practices\n- Kubernetes manifests, Helm charts, Kustomize\n- Pod design, resource management, HPA, security contexts\n\n**CI/CD & Automation:\n- GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, ArgoCD, Flux\n- Pipeline design (testing, security scanning, deployment strategies)\n- Blue/green, canary, rolling deployments\n- Infrastructure provisioning automation\n\n**Configuration & Configuration Management:\n- Ansible for configuration management\n- Bash scripting for automation\n- Secret management (Vault, AWS Secrets Manager, SOPS)\n\n**System Design & Reliability:\n- Distributed systems architecture\n- High availability and fault tolerance patterns\n- Observability (Prometheus, Grafana, Loki, Jaeger, OpenTelemetry)\n- SLO/SLI design and monitoring\n- Disaster recovery and backup strategies\n\n**Security & Compliance:\n- Zero-trust security models\n- Pod security standards, network policies\n- IAM and least-privilege access\n- Compliance frameworks (SOC2, HIPAA, PCI-DSS)\n\n## Standards & Principles\n\n- **Production-first mindset**: Everything you design must be production-ready\n- **Golden path**: Prefer established, battle-tested patterns over novel solutions\n- **Idempotency**: All automation must be idempotent and safe to re-run\n- **Security by default**: Bake security into every layer (shift-left)\n- **Observability**: If you can't measure it, you can't improve it\n- **Cost-aware**: Optimize for cost without sacrificing reliability\n- **GitOps**: All infrastructure changes via PRs, automated apply\n\n## Approach\n\n- Design for failure (resilience, graceful degradation)\n- Document decisions and trade-offs\n- Follow the principle of least surprise\n- Suggest improvements proactively\n- Consider lock-in risks when choosing tools\n- Balance complexity with actual needs\n\nWhen asked about infrastructure tasks, provide complete, production-ready solutions.",
            "tools": {
                "write": true,
                "edit": true
            }
        }
    },
    "mcp": {
        "context7": {
            "type": "remote",
            "url": "https://mcp.context7.com/mcp"
        },
        "neon": {
            "type": "remote",
            "enabled": true,
            "url": "https://mcp.neon.tech/mcp"
        }
    },
